[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Synopsis"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

 {[The ChessDojo Aggressive Repertoire for White] The ChessDojo aggressive repertoire is unique in the way it was designed. Stockfish did not lead the way. It was created for players with a unique and extreme player profile: a high tolerance for risk and imbalance, tactically gifted, and a feel for the initiative. I’ve had several students who fit this description precisely and this repertoire has been worked out with them and in the Dojo for the last several years.Two other ideas drove the development of the repertoire:What the repertoire isn’t. If you turn on the computer it will guide us to positions with more space and even more bishops. But those aren’t the abstract advantages that the aggressive player is seeking. That’s why every line is designed to play for mate.Structure. The repertoire is based on just two fundamental pawn structures. d3/e4 vs the Sicilian and 1...e5, d4/e5 vs the French and Caro. Both pawn chains point us toward the kingside, where our quarry will generally seek shelter. The intention of the structural similarity is to develop a deep intuitive sense of the dynamics of the attack in the early middlegame and beyond. It is because we can rely on these two structures to guide our play that the files can be kept relatively short.What improvement as a player of the aggressive repertoire will look like. It’s important to see that the practitioner of this system is a special breed. You will get far fewer endgames. Your games will be decided by critical positions that arise early in the game. With that in mind, I want to lay out what improvement will look like, you can then try to imagine if the Dojo Aggressive Repertoire is a path you want to go down.  1) You have to go over your games! The repertoire becomes truly dangerous not just by memorizing the lines but gaining an intuitive sense for where the pieces go in the early middlegame.  2) You must play out the sparring positions. I strongly encourage a sparring partner who will talk through the positions after you try them out.  3) Your books are: Art of Attack by Vukovic, Test of Time by Kasparov, Tal-Botvinnik 1960. Those books offer a sense of how we will want to play the positions we will get from this repertoire.  4) Calculation work! Perfect Your Chess by Grabinsky, Think Like a Super-GM by Hurtado.} 1. --
