2. Bc4 {A romantic move with many fresh ideas for the attacking player.Strategy: The setup is simple, we point our pawn chain to the kingside with d3 and then start charging with f4. Note the similarities to a King's Indian - Instead of ...d6, ...e5 and then ...f5, we have d3-e4 and then f4. Note also that in contrast to a King's Indian our bishop is outside the pawn chain and that we get our f4-break with much less fuss.Let's also take a moment to think about the dreaded London System: the Bishop's Opening is a mirror image of the London! First, notice how the pointing of the pawns changes the flavor of the game entirely. We will be attacking the kingside and the king. In the traditional London, White aims for a nagging yank on the queenside. Like with the London though, a key part of our play will be how we deal with Black harassing our bishop on c4 (in the London the bishop is, of course, on f4). We will need to be creative and flexible. Like with the London, it's important to understand that while our c4-bishop looks pretty, our dark-squared bishop is our best piece. The bishop from c1 moves easily through our pawn chain. He is the mortar and the pawns are the bricks.Making things easy: The Bishop's Opening avoids the dreariness of names like Petroff, Berlin, and Marshall. It's much less known and explored than traditional2.Nf3lines. After learning a couple forcing lines the white player should expect to develop a general feel as to where the pieces go. We use the same pawn structure (d3-e4 with a later f4) - with our light-squared bishop outside the chain - against the Sicilian. So we are aiming for a familiarity with early middlegame attacking setups and dynamics.Style: Expect violence. The Bishop's Opening, and every other opening in our aggressive repertoire, is not designed to give us some small advantage that only the computer understands. The repertoire aims to create an attack, with extreme danger and a lack of balance for both sides.2.Nc3will transpose,