2. Nf6 {2...Bc5will transpose to either2...Nc6or2...Nf6.} 
3. Nc3 {For centuries this was thought to be unplayable (!) but we have a novel approach.3.d3is our alternate variation.} 
3. Nc6
4. d3
4. Bc5
5. f4
5. O-O {This is the variation the Dojo suggests for Black, it's the most natural and contains many tricks.} 
6. Nf3 {6.f5?the question with the bold f5-push is always: Can Black play ...d5 in response? Here they can.6...d5!7.Nxd5Nxe4!-+don't fall for this!} 
6. Ng4 {If Black is going to play ...Ng4 then this is the position they should do it because ...d5 can be played with tempo.} 
7. Ng5
7. h6 {Note: whenever Black makes this move our intuition should start dreaming about g4-g5. I.e. we view ...h6 as a possible lever to open the king's position.} 
8. f5
8. Nf6
9. h4 {This setup with the h-pawn is sometimes called the 'fishing pole.' Black can never take the knight because it will unleash the rook on h1 along the h-file, meanwhile, we prepare g4-g5.} 
9. d6 {9...hxg510.hxg5Ne811.Qh5+-mate is coming.} 
10. g4 {We are going to roll Black up.} 
10. Qe8
11. Nxf7
11. Rxf7
12. g5 {A pattern to know for our opening!} 
