[Black "2) 1...c5 with 3...g6"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. c5
2. Nc3 {The Closed Sicilian.Strategy: like in our Bishop's Opening we want to move our light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain, play d3 and aim for f4. Our pawns point toward the kingside and we are playing for mate. Making it easy: this system isn't just about memorizing some lines, it's about playing a set of structures. And these structures have many dynamic similarities to our Bishop's Opening.Style: expect violence and critical positions early. Friend of the ChessDojo GM Eugene Perelshteyn has a nice course out on the Grand Prix which you can compare to this. Surprisingly none of the lines are the same. Eugene is interested in complicated and paradoxical lines that have the approval of his supercomputer. Our system is built on the idea of familiar structures that lead to an attack.} 
2. Nc6
3. Bb5 {The idea is simple and elegant: if Black lets us take we will get our structure with d3/f4 AND we will have a favorable version of the Rossolimo. The Rossolimo is1.e4c52.Nf3Nc63.Bb5g6Bxc6.The secret of the modern Rossolimo has been that Black's damaged pawns make it difficult for Black to conduct their usual queenside play. And Nimzovitch's rule certainly applies here: the further up the board the damaged pawns progress the weaker they will become.We need to see that we have a favorable Rossolimo because with our pawn on f4, not blocked by a knight on f3, we can jump-start our initiative on the kingside. And even more important: it's a structure we are familiar with.} 
3. g6
4. Bxc6
4. dxc6
5. d3
5. Bg7
6. f4 {White's attack on the kingside follows our usual template.} 
