3. e5 {We create a French structure.Strategy: Our pawn chain points to the kingside, this is our clue that is our side of the board, where we would like to attack. It's our side because it's easier for us to transfer force (pieces) there. This means that we are willing to make weaknesses there, because we have the juice to defend them. We want Black to give us something (anything!) there (on the kingside) for us to sink our teeth into.After ...e6, Black's pawns will be pointing to the queenside, Black will want to create drama there before they get mated. Black can also play for ...c5 and drama against our d4-pawn.Making things easy: Our attacking formations and ideas will be similar to our system against the French. Like our e5 in the French this3.e5dramatically reduces Black's options.By contrast, the classical3.Nc3allows:3...dxe44.Nxe4Bf53...dxe44.Nxe4Nd73...dxe44.Nxe4Nf65.Nxf6gxf63...dxe44.Nxe4Nf65.Nxf6exf6- all of which are very playable.Style:3.Nc3generally leads to technical positions, with3.e5we are playing for mate. Expect violence.} 
3. Bf5 {Let's talk about Black's dreams: The whole reason the Caro was invented was to avoid having a bad French bishop. Here the Caro player wants to play ...e6 and then ...c5 to get a French without having the bad French bishop. The problem with this dream is that it takes forever. So our plan is fairly simple: to take the initiative before Black achieves their ideal French.} 
4. h4 {It's important to see the positional advantages of this very tactical move: we prevent Black from playing the necessary ...e6 (if Black does we will win the f5-bishop). And we want to play on our strong side of the board, we are allowed to make potential weaknesses on our strong side because our force count is stronger there.} 
4. h5 {This is Black's best but also a big concession: Black doesn't want to make pawn moves on their weak side because they give us weaknesses to work with. The g5 hole is now glaring. Note also that if Black now ever wants to do the standard French break with ...f6 then g6 will also be weak.} 
5. Bg5 {We again prevent ...e6 and force Black to go on a queen adventure. Bd3 is also a fine move, but it's not what we are looking for in our repertoire. Bd3 plays for a spatial advantage, we are playing for mate. The coming positions are incredibly tactical and full of hidden ideas. Learn the paths through this forest, your opponents will lose their way.} 
5. Qb6 {Black must play ...e6 to complete their development.} 
6. Bd3 {A very deep move!} 
6. Bxd3
7. Qxd3 {Note that we win a tempo with this recapture.} 
7. Qxb2 {You will get this position.} 
8. e6 {One of the most interesting positions I've ever come across - Black is, in fact, lost!} 
8. Qxa1 {The prize they came for!} 
9. Qb3
9. b5 {...b6 would be similar. Let's understand on a schematic level why Black is toast: after Nf3 and O-O we will win the queen with Nc3 or Nbd2. At that point, Black will technically be up in material (!), but the reason they are lost is that Black can't develop or coordinate the pieces. That's the perfect arena for our queen to start picking up the field mice and bopping em on the head.Note that this position can be used as a template for the common dynamic of queen vs a motley crew of pieces. It occurs often when we play attacking chess. The simple question we need to ask at the end of such variations is: Can Black put their legos together?} 
10. Nf3
10. Nf6
11. O-O
11. fxe6
12. Nc3 {Our queen will find a way in.} 
