1. e4
1. g6 {This is sometimes called the Modern, it is a very close cousin to the Pirc.} 
2. d4
2. Bg7
3. Nc3
3. d6 {3...a64.Be3b55.Qd2Bb76.f3d6transposes to 3...d6.} 
4. Be3 {This is our setup against the Pirc as well. Transpositions between the two lines are common.} 
4. a6
5. Qd2
5. b5 {Not a bad option for those determined to get an aggressive and violent position as Black. While the computer despises this position for Black it scores quite well in human play.Let's talk about Black's dreams: by delaying ....Nf6 Black prevents any Bh6 plan and leaves e4-e5 without a point. The drawbacks of this plan are obvious: The king on e8 will be scrambling in the pocket, it's hard for the h8-rook to get involved and the g8-knight might find it impossible to actually ever get out.} 
6. O-O-O
6. Bb7
7. f3 {Note the advantages of this move over7.Bd3.Bd3 gets in the way of the d-file and doesn't control g4. That square is important to prevent ...Ng4 and to have the option of playing g4.Note as well that if our h1-rook can become useful in any way where it stands after h4-h5 then we can also then call the bishop on f1 developed where it stands.} 
7. Nd7
8. h4 {Our play could not be more direct.} 
8. h5
9. Nh3 {Now we know where our knight wants to go. Black can now play various moves but we are guaranteed a sustained attack with our knight on g5.} 
9. Ngf6
10. Ng5
10. O-O
11. g4 {A common sacrifice for our attack.} 
11. hxg4
12. h5 {Let's open the cage!} 
12. gxh5
13. fxg4 {A classic breakthrough, our queen is coming to h2 and Black is going to get mated.} 
