6. Nc3
6. d4 {This common human move shows a poor understanding of chess and helps us visualize the dreams of our opening: We get a King's Indian structure where our normally bad bishop is very active (the bishop on b3).} 
7. Ne2 {The following shows best play for both sides.7...O-O8.O-Oc59.Ng3Nc610.Nh4g611.h3!→it's always useful to control this square, we stop both a later ...Bg4 and ...Ng4. We have two basic plans here: Nf3-g5 and f4. The Dojo will also always check if Nhf5 works. The position will become hot.In the ensuing mess we DO NOT want to ever trade our dark-squared bishop. He is our best piece and the key to any attack. That is why for example we are not in a rush to play Bg5 or Bh6 as those moves set Black up to trade their nasty bishop with ...Be7 and ...Bf8.} 
