1. e4
1. c5
2. Nc3 {The Closed Sicilian.Strategy: like in our Bishop's Opening we want to move our light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain, play d3 and aim for f4. Our pawns point toward the kingside and we are playing for mate. Making it easy: this system isn't just about memorizing some lines, it's about playing a set of structures. And these structures have many dynamic similarities to our Bishop's Opening.Style: expect violence and critical positions early. Friend of the ChessDojo GM Eugene Perelshteyn has a nice course out on the Grand Prix which you can compare to this. Surprisingly none of the lines are the same. Eugene is interested in complicated and paradoxical lines that have the approval of his supercomputer. Our system is built on the idea of familiar structures that lead to an attack.} 
2. e6 {Black might be tricking himself with this move: It's known as an antidote to the closed Sicilian, but Black must be willing to play one of the ...e6 Open Sicilians. And that is where we are now headed. No matter whether he plays a Taimanov, Kan, or Scheveningen our setup will be the same, it's an EZ system!} 
3. Nf3 {Against ...e6 we cannot play our regular setup because ...d5 is coming on f4. It might seem strange to now play an open Sicilian, but we have a simple setup against ...e6 that isn't too distant from the Grand Prix we will find in other lines. Instead of a pawn, we'll put our bishop on d3 and then play for f4.} 
3. d6
4. d4
4. cxd4
5. Nxd4
5. Nf6 {The Scheveningen.} 
6. Bd3 {Our plan is simple: O-O, Be3 if necessary, Kh1, f4 and we play for mate.The following is a sample line.6...a67.O-OBe78.Kh1O-O9.f4Qc710.Be3Nc611.Qf3Bd712.Qg3b513.a3Nxd414.Bxd4Bc615.Rae1with a strong attacking setup.} 
