2. Nc3 {The Closed Sicilian.Strategy: like in our Bishop's Opening we want to move our light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain, play d3 and aim for f4. Our pawns point toward the kingside and we are playing for mate. Making it easy: this system isn't just about memorizing some lines, it's about playing a set of structures. And these structures have many dynamic similarities to our Bishop's Opening.Style: expect violence and critical positions early. Friend of the ChessDojo GM Eugene Perelshteyn has a nice course out on the Grand Prix which you can compare to this. Surprisingly none of the lines are the same. Eugene is interested in complicated and paradoxical lines that have the approval of his supercomputer. Our system is built on the idea of familiar structures that lead to an attack.} 
2. d6 {Najdorf players will often play this move order. Our play now becomes straightforward: we will trade off our bad bishop with Bb5 and achieve our d3/e4/f4 attacking setup.} 
3. f4 {Like with our Bishop's opening we are really aiming for a King's Indian style setup without the bad bishop and without a sad dance where we bring our knight out and then move him back so the f-pawn can move.Let's talk about the dreams of Frederico the f-pawn. In the Bishop's opening Frederico has friction with a pawn on e5 and that means that we can expect freedom for our bishop on c1 and our rook on f1, Fred will easily get out of the way.Here it's different, we must find creative ways for Fred to get out of the way! f5 should be our default. We need to be ready to sack Fred to get our pieces humming.} 
3. Nc6
4. Nf3
4. g6
5. Bb5 {Once our bad bishop has a clear job our attack becomes fairly straightforward..} 
5. Bg7
6. Bxc6+
6. bxc6
7. d3
7. Nf6 {Note: this position can also arrive for us through1.e4c52.Nc3Nc63.Bb5g6(or 3...e6)4.Bxc6bxc6(!)} 
8. O-O
8. O-O
9. Qe1 {White has a lovely attack that they can take his time with. We are looking to eventually play f5. And we want to avoid allowing Black to open the position for their light-squared bishop.} 
