4. a6 {A secret that's hard to understand at first glance is that if Black doesn't play this move right away we will have options to play back to a4 or c4 later because there will be no ...c4-move trapping the bishop, because we will have traded on d4. We see this in the variations with4...e6and4...g6.} 
5. Bd3 {Black claims that their development disadvantage is offset by our odd bishop on d3. We have three methods to free our position:1)5...--6.Nxd4cxd47.Ne2--and8.c32)5...--6.b4and3) simply moving the bishop. We need to be flexible in choosing between these three.} 
5. Nc6 {What a dance! Black realizes that Nxd4 followed by Ne2 and c3 will free our position - and is willing to waste another tempo.} 
6. O-O
6. d6
7. Bc4 {Since we can meet ...b5 with Bd5. d4, opening the position with a huge lead in development is next.} 
