[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) French (1.e4 e6 2.d4)"]
[Black "French with 6...cxd4 & 7...Bd7 #4"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e6
2. d4
2. d5
3. e5 {Strategy: Our pawn chain points to the kingside, our side of the board, where we would like to attack. It's our side because it's easier for us to transfer force (pieces) there. This means that we are ok with making weaknesses there, for we have the juice to defend them. And we want Black to give us something (anything!) there (on the kingside) for us to sink our teeth into. Black's pawns point to the queenside. Black will need to make drama there and against our d4 point to avoid getting mated.Making things easy: Like our3.e5vs the Caro, we dramatically limit Black's options. By contrast the traditional3.Nc3allows the Winawer (...Bb4) and Steinitz (...Nf6), both of which will give Black the kind of trench warfare that encouraged them to play the French in the first place.3.Nd2allows even more options, with3...c5,3...Nf6and even3...Be7.Style: For hundreds of years white players have tried to make an attacking formation with Nf3 and Bd3 work. It's now possible.} 
3. c5
4. c3
4. Nc6
5. Nf3
5. Qb6
6. Bd3 {The following idea came to me in a dream! I've played the French for years and was trying to imagine what my tribe finds especially unpleasant.We don't mind the bad bishop, we console ourselves with the mantra: 'There's no such thing as bad bishops, only bad players.' And we obviously don't mind having less space. What we don't like is when things blow up and we lose control!In 2020 I published a video called 'an EZ system against the French.' Since then it's been played by Magnus Carlsen and many other top GMs - I'm stunned every time I think of something that came from my head landing in Carlsen's! The system has been developed and tested since then.} 
6. cxd4
7. O-O {7.cxd4Bd78.O-ONxd49.Nxd4Qxd410.Nc3the Milner-Barry Gambit which I've faced many times, this was the kind of unpleasantness my French tribe doesn't like and the inspiration for our System against the French.} 
7. Bd7
8. Re1 {Let's talk for a moment about this move and the old-school idea of overprotection. Imagine you are Black's king, castling short is the only viable long-term haven. But you'll never be safe with the pawn on e5, as the pawn gives White the ability to increase our force count on the kingside. And this is exactly where the black king wants to hide.That is why White must foresee Black wanting ...f6 at some point. That break will give Black the option of defending their king laterally, with say the queen on c7 or a rook on f7.Therefore our overprotection of e5 isn't just about protecting a pawn, we want our force to be ready to flow through that square when Black does play ...f6. You can think of e5 as the sharp point of our spear.} 
8. Nge7
9. h4 {SPARRING POSITIONThe main point of this move is to prevent Black's awkward knight on e7 from finding a post on g6. We especially don't like it there as Black will then fight for our e5 strongpoint.} 
9. Nf5
10. Bxf5
10. exf5
11. cxd4 {We are up in time and aim to fight on the dark squares.} 
11. Be7
12. Nc3
12. Be6
13. Bg5 {We trade Black's good bishop and aim to play on the dark squares, with plans like Na4-c5 and Ne2-f4.} 
