[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. d5 {I'm not sure why this opening exists but it's common enough that we should elaborate on the pain that we will inflict upon Black's soul.} 
2. exd5
2. Nf6 {If I had to play the Scandi I'd at least try this.} 
3. d4
3. Nxd5 {3...Bg44.Nf3Nxd5transposes.} 
4. Nf3 {What's nice about this move is that we have a simple plan against ...Bg4 - really the only move we should be concerned with} 
4. Bg4
5. Be2 {SPARRING POSITIONWe intend Ne5 at our convenience.} 
5. e6
6. O-O
6. Be7
7. h3
7. Bxf3
8. Bxf3 {This loss of the light squares is common in the Scandi. Our basic plan here is simple: after Black loses a tempo dealing with the threat of c4 we will put our pawns on dark squares to compliment our unopposed bishop (c3) and start bringing our knight in. Black's long-term problem is that it's always bad news if they open the position for our monster f3-bishop.} 
