[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) Alekhine (1.e4 Nf6 2.e5)"]
[Black "Alekhine with 4...Bg4 & 5...Nc6 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. Nf6 {An attacking player's reaction to this move should be: I can now turn this defender of Black's king into a nag.} 
2. e5
2. Nd5
3. d4
3. d6
4. Nf3 {Strategy. We tell Black that our e5-pawn is the tip of our spear and it's not going away. We also say that the kingside is our side and Black's force count is low there. If they take we intend to recapture with the knight. Making it easy. We just need to understand the couple tries Black has to undermine our e5 strongpoint.Style. We DO NOT play for space with c4 and f4. We are playing for mate.} 
4. Bg4 {The second we see this move we should think: 'light squares'. We'll see several variations where Black will be missing their bishop.} 
5. Be2
5. Nc6
6. c4
6. Nb6
7. e6 {A familiar theme from our system against the Caro. It's not just that Black's king is weak but that it's difficult to develop their kingside.} 
7. Bxe6
8. d5 {Whoops.} 
