7. f5 {Knowing when to play this move is a key skill of the repertoire. In general, we can say that it's a good idea if Black can't organize some kind of violent ...d5 counterstrike.The fact that Black gave us a tempo with ...a6 was a good omen for us to go for it. Black has to kick now, the bishop on c8 is officially a problem, and the black king has no safe space.} 
7. h6 {With this move Black stops Bg5 and g4-g5, correctly claiming that the f6-knight is critical to the defense of his king. Note that Black is also saying that he is not going to castle anytime soon.} 
8. Nd5 {White removes the f6 defender!} 
8. Na5 {Black initiates a crisis, and it's now time to think. I.e. a critical position has arisen. Note that we don't terribly mind trading off our c4-bishop. While it gives f7 a mean look, it is by far our worst bishop because all our pawns are on light squares.} 
