 {The key takeaway from this game is this: your attack won't work if all of your pieces are not playing. In my experience as a coach, the lack of sensitivity to this problem is a key factor holding back players in the 2000-2300 Fide range.If you tell them in an abstract way that they need to fix their worst pieces then of course they get it. But they don't yet feel their bad pieces. And this need to feel bad pieces escalates dramatically when we raise the stakes as we do in the aggressive repertoire.} 1. e4
1. c6
2. d4
2. d5
3. e5
3. Bf5
4. h4
4. h6
5. g4
5. Be4
6. f3
6. Bh7
7. e6
7. Qd6
8. exf7+
8. Kxf7
9. f4 {Welcome to the Dojo! An anti-intuitive move, we prevent ...e5, we intend Nf3-e5, and we are not afraid of the e4-bishop because that's the one piece we want to trade-off.} 
9. Nf6
10. Nf3
10. Be4 {10...Nxg4this is the one move we need to feel confident facing.11.Bh3h512.Ne5+→and there are no great options for Black.} 
11. Ne5+ {Played reflexively. Yes, the f3-knight intends to play Ne5. But we need to recognize that our worst piece is the knight on b1, and Black's best is the e4-bishop, the guardian of Black's weakened light squares. Moment number 1 where White didn't fix the knight.11.Nc3!Black is now strategically lost as he must give up his amazing bishop.} 
11. Ke8
12. Bd3
12. Nbd7
13. O-O {Oh no! Moment number two where White is not thinking about their worst piece.13.Nc3!Black is lost as we will win the bishop on e4 and activate our b1-knight.} 
13. e6
14. Re1 {Oh no! The rook was already doing something on f1. White needs to feel that all of the pieces need to play. Moment number three where the knight is neglected.Also note that up to this point, White still had 128 minutes from an initial 130. Players of this repertoire must understand that high-stakes positions will arise in the first fifteen moves and that we will have to think deeply about what is going on.14.Nc3!} 
14. Be7
15. c4 {Moment number four where the knight was neglected. White spent one minute on this decision.15.Nc3!} 
15. c5 {To play ...c5 or not is always Black's big question in all of the Advance Caros. In general, Black must understand that ...c5 costs a tempo and radically increases the value of time because the position will now open.} 
16. cxd5 {Let's open the game!} 
16. exd5
17. Nc3 {Better late than never!} 
17. cxd4
18. Nxe4 {Now we own the light squares, and Black is in big trouble.} 
18. dxe4
19. Bxe4 {TIME: 50 minutes (13 min think).} 
19. Nxe4
