 {JK. This is a game submitted to the ChessDojo DB by Dystopia. Using the discipline of the Dojo, Dystopia did not use the computer in their analysis. In addition to showing us how to analyze a game, this practice gives us a strong sense of his thought process. My notes are marked with JK for Jesse Kraai and are in cursive. The above Lichess ratings translate to about 1550 Fide.} 1. e4 {Going for the aggressive repertoire.} 
1. e5
2. Bc4
2. c6 {Out of book from here. I remembered the line below, also featuring an early ...c6, which was the main reason I went for 3.Nf3.2...Nf63.d3c64.Nf3d55.Bb3Bd66.Nc3dxe47.Ng5O-O8.Ncxe4Nxe49.dxe4h610.Nxf7Rxf711.Bxf7+Kxf712.Qh5+Kg813.Bxh6gxh614.Qg6+Kh815.O-O-OJK. Great memory!} 
3. Nf3 {Must be a fine move, though options like d3, d4, and Nc3 obviously exist.3.d4!JK. The exclam is mine.3...d53...exd44.Qxd4±better since there is no ...Nc6.4.exd5cxd55.Bb5+Bd7JK. Taking on d7, and then dxe5 has to be a nice position for White.6.Qe2∞maybe this is slightly better for White. I calculated this during the game but did not think it was too much (if anything at all).} 
3. d5 {3...d64.d4Nd74...exd45.Qxd4±5.O-O⩲this looks like a Philidor, possibly a direct transposition. I figured this was Black's best try, but I like White in these positions.3...Nf6?4.Nxe5±} 
4. Bb3 {JK. There is one fundamental question in this variation: will the b3-bishop be a hero or a zero? The evaluation of the position will hinge on the answer.} 
4. Nf6
5. O-O {Maybe I should have played5.h3to prevent ...Bg4, but losing the tempo still looks weird to me.JK. White definitely should have played Nc3, the success of our play depends on whether we can open the b3-f7 diagonal.5.Nc3⩲gives us an advantageous version of the alternative line given in our repertoire. Here we see Nc3 instead of d3, allowing us immediate pressure on d5 and the possibility of blowing everything open with d4. Note that the natural ...Bd6 leaves d5 simply unguarded.} 
5. Bg4 {Somehow this move flew under my radar. I mostly considered ...Bd6 and ...Nbd7, defending e5 directly.JK. Question mark is mine. With ...Nxe4, Black could have locked our b3-bishop out of the game and achieved easy equality.5...Nbd76.Re1Be77.d4→5...Bd66.Re1Nbd76...O-O7.exd5cxd58.Nxe5±7.d3⩲} 
6. exd5 {JK. Correct! We open the position before Black can castle.6.d4!?exd47.Qxd4Bxf38.gxf3I did not want to mess with this during the game, but it might be strong. Now I see a nice tactical idea:8...dxe4??8...Be7it seems like Black needs to castle quickly, but this might not even work.9.e5Nfd710.e6looks very good for White to me.9.Bxf7++-} 
6. Nxd5 {This surprised me. ...cxd5 looks more natural and is probably the better move.JK. Definitely not a move that suits the position. Black is not aware of the strategic conception behind ...cxd5: to shut down our bishop.6...cxd57.Re17.d3Bc5⩱this also looks good for Black with the strong center. If I have to resort to d3, my play before can't have been ideal.7.h3Bxf38.Qxf3=maybe this is the best I can get. But even here the black center looks strong.JK. this is an amazing position for White because with Nc3 next, we can force the d-pawn to move, freeing our unopposed bishop on b3.7...Be78.d4e49.h3Bh510.g4Nxg411.hxg4Bxg412.Nbd2O-O-+This looks incredible for Black, who is probably winning.} 
7. h3
7. Bxf3 {Forced, since7...Bh5?8.g4Bg69.Nxe5is horrible.} 
8. Qxf3
8. Be7
9. Nc3 {Using the fact that the knight is essentially pinned and can't be defended further.JK. Simple and strong play on the light squares.9.Qg3with the same idea as on move 10 does not work because of9...Bf6and Black might keep it together.} 
9. Nf6 {A practitioner of the Aggressive Repertoire is required to celebrate every time they win a tempo.9...Nxc3?10.Bxf7+Kd711.Qf5++-9...Nf4I missed this move during the game (saw it right after I made my move...). I do not think it is particularly good, however.10.g3or simply 10.Kh2, defending the h-pawn and preparing g3 next.10...Nxh3+11.Kg2Ng512.Qh5O-O13.Rh1→} 
10. Qg3 {This was the point of the previous move. e5 and g7 are both hanging, so I win a pawn.} 
10. O-O
11. Qxe5 {JK. After a series of precise moves, White has emerged with a clear center pawn up, AND they have an unopposed light-squared bishop looking at f7.} 
11. Nbd7 {11...Bd6probably more precise since the queen has to stay on the e-file and runs into another tempo by ...Re8. I still don't think Black has sufficient compensation for the pawn.12.Qd4??Bh2+} 
12. Qf5
12. Nc5
13. d3 {This looked very natural to me. The bishop is not doing much, and the opening of the a-file is nice for my rook.} 
13. h6
14. Be3 {14.Bf4I considered this since14...g5??15.Qg6+is nice, but Black is not forced to play ...g5.} 
14. Nxb3
15. axb3 {This shows the advantage of having the bishop on e3. Black has to waste another tempo.} 
15. a6 {15...b6here I thought that16.Ra6with Rfa1 next looked extremely unpleasant for Black.} 
16. Rfe1 {Sticking a knight on c5 (or a5) must be extremely strong here. I could not quite make it work during the game and stuck to a simpler approach which must also be very comfortable.} 
16. Re8 {16...Qc7on this (or any slow move by Black), I had the idea of17.Bb6!?Qxb618.Rxe7which looked attractive to me.} 
17. Re2 {The rook on a1 is not doing much, so doubling on the only semi-open file must be good.} 
17. Qc7
18. Bf4 {18.Rae1!the alternative was to double up first so that Bf4 next forces the queen to keep contact with the bishop. I can't even find a good move for Black here, so this is probably even better.} 
18. Qd8 {18...Bd619.Bxd6Qxd620.Rae1±is also very pleasant.18...Qb619.Rae1Kf820.Rxe7!Rxe721.Bd6+-} 
19. Rae1 {This looks natural but must be a mistake. The white queen is light on squares after g6.19.Ne4Nxe420.Qxe4±This looks like it keeps a big advantage.} 
19. g6 {I missed this during the game, and not I am probably not even better anymore.JK. Here we see an interesting psychological detail that afflicts almost all chess players: Dystopia feels bad, even guilty, because of missing g6 (and should!), so they think that they deserve to be punished - a karmic punishment. But chess doesn't believe in Karma!} 
20. Qe5 {The only square.} 
20. Kh7 {I don't understand this move, the bishop discoveries look so natural. Perhaps they missed the knight defending the rook on e8 and thought I had Qxe8 after the bishop moved.20...Ba3JK. White is still winning here! We can take the rook on e8.21.Qc7JK21.Qxe8+Nxe822.Rxe8+Qxe823.Rxe8+Rxe824.bxa3+-Bxb222.Qxd8Raxd823.Rxe8+Rxe824.Rxe8+Nxe825.Ne4=this looks pretty forced and equal.} 
21. Qc7 {And we are back on track.} 
21. Qxc7
