17. Qh3 {JK. Besides showing some nice repertoire play against a Super-GM, I included this game to show what success in the aggressive repertoire will ultimately come down to calculation and a feel for the initiative. To develop these skills, you have to review your games. The notes to f5! were all done without the computer.TIME: I have 57 mins left.JK. The unbearable sadness of missing f5 is that James didn't spend any time on what was obviously a critical position. One way to suspect that a critical position might be at hand is to feel the loss of initiative after Qh3, that it is too slow. This feel is developed by studying your own games, especially if one lacks this where this one missed chance leads to a long-term downward trend.I need to learn how to do nothing. Like a3, Rf2, or h3. Solid moves that might be needed and definitely don't do damage. So why didn't I play f5? - I was afraid to get too committed. - I didn't see that in some variations his queen was hanging. Afterward, he said he didn't think I had anything.17.f5!JK. The only alteration I've made to the following human notes was to prune some of the variations. I was considering f5.17...exf5Forced.17...gxf518.Bxf5!JK. Since Black cannot take, our force count on the kingside is overwhelming.18...exf519.Qg3+Kh820.e6++-Winning the queen. This is one of the tricks White must see to play f5.18.Rxf5!!Forcing.18...gxf518...Rfe819.Raf1!Be619...gxf520.Rxf5Bf820...Qc621.e6Qxe622.Rg5+Bxg523.Qxg5+Qg623...Kf824.Bg7+Kg825.Bf6+24.Bxg621.Qg3+Bg722.Rg5Kh823.Rxg7+-20.R5f3+-JK. White's force count is too strong, and Black has no counterplay. We can play h4-h5 next.18...Be619.Rh5!f519...gxh520.Qe4f521.exf6Rf721...Bf522.Qxf5Bxf623.Qxh722.Qxa8++-19...Bg420.Rg5Bxg521.Qxg5Be622.Qh6Rfc823.Rf1Qd824.Rxf7!24.Rf424.Rf324...Kxf724...Bxf725.e6Qf826.Qg5Bxe627.Bxg6Rc528.Bf5+Kf729.Qh5+Ke730.Bxc5+d631.Qxh7+Qf732.Qh4+Kd733.Qd4Bxf534.Qxd6+Kc835.Qc6+Kd825.Qxh7+Kf826.Qh6+Ke727.Qg7+Bf728.e6+-20.exf6Bxf621.Qh6Bxd4+22.cxd4d623.Bxg6hxg624.Qh8+Kf725.Rh7+Ke826.Qxf8+Kxf827.Rxc7+-18...Rfc819.e6!gxf520.Qh6f621.Bxf5+-18...Qc619.Qh6!gxf519...Be420.Rf6!Qd521.e6fxe622.Rxg6++-20.e6f621.Bxf5+-19.Qg3+!JK. While the above variations are very complicated, this is really the only thing you need to see to play f5!I Needed to see just four moves ahead. All I had to do was look at all the checks until there were no more checks. Check19...Kh8Only move.20.e6+Check. This should have been an easy thing to see.17.h4bxa417...Bxh418.Qh3Be719.g418.h5Kh819.hxg6fxg620.Bxg6hxg621.f5gxf522.Qh6+Kg823.Qg6+Kh8} 
