 {This game is from the DC Chess League. G/90 + 30. I played this exact line of the Caro in my last league game, but did not play the crucial c4. I was a bit more prepared for this one.JK. All notes by Charlie Compton unless in cursive and marked JK for Jesse Kraai. This game was submitted to the ChessDojo annotated games database. It is the discipline of the Dojo to not use the engine for the analysis of our games. Charlie's notes provide an example of how it's done and give us a glimpse into his human view of the game.} 1. e4
1. c6
2. d4
2. d5
3. e5
3. Bf5
4. h4
4. h5 {4...h65.g4Be45...Bd7is the best move in this position, but it is very hard to play from the perspective of a Caro player trying to avoid the French bishop.6.h56.f3Bh77.e6!thematic idea in these lines.7...fxe68.Bd3Bxd39.Qxd3Qd610.f4±} 
5. Bg5 {The Caveman variation. I have been playing this for a couple of years now, and it always yields dynamic, if a bit weird, positions. The point is that Black cannot play ...e6, with ideas to trade off light-squared bishops and have a kingside attack.} 
5. Qb6
6. Bd3
6. Qxd4 {6...Bxd3the most common response.7.Qxd3e67...Qa6!?this is the line I have had the most trouble with. The endgame is better for Black, or at least equal, so White must keep the queen, but it allows Black to develop more and create a stable position.8.Qh3Threatening mate in8...e69.Nc3Bb410.Nge2⩲7...Qxb2?!8.e6fxe69.Nf3Nd79...Qxa1?10.Qb3trapping the queen and threatening Qxb7.10...b511.O-Ob412.Qxb4Qxa213.Qb7+-the queen is saved, but the cost is too high.8.Nd2c59.c4→} 
7. Nf3
7. Qg4
8. Bxf5 {Trading seems a bit weird, but the idea is to take the black queen off the 4th rank so it can't swing across the board. Plus, f5 is not a great square for the queen, so it will have to be relocated eventually, costing yet another tempo.} 
8. Qxf5
9. O-O {9.c4Qe4+10.Be3e6I remember when I looked over the last game I played in this line that the computer likes this and the early c4, but I don't fully get it and did not want to try this OTB.10...Qxc411.e6fxe612.Nbd2Qg413.Qb311.Nbd2Qd3⩱} 
9. e6 {9...Qd710.c4e6my opponent suggested that this might have been better for Black in our post-mortem, but it obviously seems less than desirable visually. That said, Black's position is solid, and White has no clear way in. White should have compensation for the pawn, but it could easily be lost with imprecise play.10...dxc411.Qc211.Nc3Nh612.Qc2Na613.Rad1⩲9...f6I was worried he would play this as I know it is a computer line and that I have to play the crazy10.c4JK. See the game Altucher-Quirke.10...fxg511.cxd5cxd512.Nc3e613.Nb5I didn't even remember up to this point, so I'm glad I didn't have to try this OTB!} 
10. c4 {White has to strike at the center immediately to try to create some instability in Black's position. The king is in the center, so dynamic play is called for.} 
10. Nd7
11. cxd5
11. exd5 {Strangely, I think this is the best move, even though it opens up possibilities with the e-file.If11...cxd512.Nc3a613.Rc1Bc5±Black is still too open, and White is ready to attack.13...Nxe5?greed is not good here.14.Nxe5Qxe515.Re1Qd616.Nxd514.Na4Be714...Ba715.Rc715.Rc7and White has the 7th rank and all the chances.} 
12. Nd4 {This move opened up a tempo-gaining move in Qg4 that I did not see.Better is12.Nc3JK. A common problem we've seen for White is the urgent need to get this piece to do something.12...Be713.Re1Bxg514.Nxg5Nc515.e6Nxe615...fxe6??16.b4!16.Qb3where there are still tactical chances and some dynamic factors in play.16...b617.Re3Ne7∞17...d4?18.Nxe6dxe319.Nxg7+Kf820.Nxf5} 
12. Qg6 {12...Qg4!Black has gotten his queen back to a better square and is threatening to trade queens to neutralize the attack.13.e613.f3??Qxd4+14.Qxd4Bc513...fxe614.Qxg414.Nxe6Qxe615.Re1Ne516.f4Bd617.fxe5Bc5+17...Bxe518.Bf418.Kh1Nh6-+White is still down a pawn, and the black king is in the center, but the e5-pawn blocks so much of the attacking potential.14...hxg4} 
13. Re1 {13.e6?fxe614.Re1e5and Black is stable as the e-file can't be opened.15.f4e413.Nc3JK. This is what I want!} 
13. Be7 {13...Nc514.Nd214.e6?f615.Be3Nd316.Re2∞14...Nh615.N2f3∞this seems okay for Black, but the issues around king safety remain, and it is easy to have a misstep.} 
14. e6
14. Ndf6 {This blocks the queen from defending e6. It just adds more tactical possibilities for White.Better would be14...Nc515.exf7+Kxf716.Nd2Re817.N2f3+-this is still a bad position, but more defendable.} 
15. exf7+
15. Kxf7 {15...Qxf716.Ne616...Bd617.Nc7+Kd718.Nxa8+-} 
16. Nc3 {JK. White has a winning attack.} 
16. Re8
17. Nf3 {Threatening to fork on e5 and getting the knight ready to leap to a square like g5.17.Qe2?Bc5} 
17. Ng4
18. Bxe7 {I took a long time on this move since it seemed bad to trade off a piece when attacking a pawn down, but the knight will be better than the bishop on that square, and Black is losing a crucial defender.18.Qe2N8f6=and it is not clear how White can use their advantage} 
18. Rxe7
19. Ng5+
19. Ke8 {19...Kf820.Qf3+N8f621.Qf4Qe822.Rxe7Qxe723.Qb8+Ne824.Kf1threatening Re1.24...Rh625.Re1Qd726.Qxa7+-the White queen should be able to come back over to the kingside via the diagonal. Black's lack of king safety is still an issue.} 
20. Qb3 {Here I really wanted to play20.Nxd5cxd520...Qd621.Nxe7Qxd122.Raxd1Nxe721.Qxd5and I was pretty confident it was winning. However, I was playing in a league game, and we needed at least a draw, most likely, so I didn't want to push too hard. Plus, the game move seemed pretty strong itself.21...N8f621...Qc622.Qf7+!!22.Rxe7+Nxe723.Qf7+Kd824.Rd1+Kc825.Qxe7+-22...Kd823.Qf8+Kd724.Rad1+Kc725.Rxe7+Nxe726.Qxe7+Kb827.Qxg7+-22.Rxe7+Kxe723.Re1+Kf824.Qc5+Kg825.Qc8+Ne826.Qxe8+Qxe827.Rxe8} 
20. Qd6
21. g3
21. Qc5 {This move looks nice with the mating attack, but it takes Black away from being able to get to the kingside to protect crucial squares on f5 and g6.21...Rh6lending some protection to c6 after b7 falls22.Qxb7Rf623.Rxe7+Nxe724.Re1Nxf224...Rxf2??25.Qa8+25.Qc8+Qd826.Rxe7+Kxe727.Qe6+Kf828.Nh725...Qd825.Qa8+Qd826.Qxa7±and White is better, but Black has a lot more fight.} 
22. Qc2
22. Rh6 {22...N8h623.Ne6Qd624.Nxd5!!cxd525.Qc8+Kf726.Ng5+Kg627.Qxh8+-} 
23. Qf5
23. Kd8
24. Nf7+ {24.Nce4!!I missed this OTB. Another piece enters the attack due to the pin on the d-pawn.JK. Note that we will find this move if we are constantly sensitive to the need to do something with our worst piece.24...dxe424...Qb425.Qf8+Kc726.Nf7Kb626...Rf6??27.Qd827.Nxh625.Qxc5} 
24. Rxf7
25. Qxf7
25. N8f6 {Cutting off the White queen from defense, but it is not enough.Black would love to play25...Rf6but that fails to26.Re8} 
26. Re2 {Simple defending move that also allows the rooks to double for mate threats.} 
26. d4
27. Rae1 {Renewing mate threats on e8.} 
27. Rh8 {27...Ne328.fxe328.Rxe3dxe329.Rxe328...dxc3} 
28. Ne4
28. Rf8
29. Qxf6+ {1-0 White wins. Taking on b7 might have been slightly better, but this ends the game pretty decisively, and Black resigned.} 
*
