 {JK. This game was annotated by Yosseff and submitted to the ChessDojo annotated games database. Like all annotations at the dojo, they are done without the help of the computer. My notes are in cursive and marked 'JK' for Jesse Kraai. Yosseff's rating translated to Fide is about 1600.} 1. e4 {I think this game shows how much venom the aggressive repertoire's Caro lines have in them: If I blundered a piece in one move and it is still so easy to lose with Black, being a rook up.} 
1. c6
2. d4
2. d5
3. e5
3. Bf5
4. h4
4. h5
5. Bg5
5. Qb6 {I didn't exactly remember my line for a minute or two.} 
6. Bd3
6. Qxb2 {6...Bxd37.Qxd3Qxb28.e6Qxa19.Qb3the aggressive repertoire choice.} 
7. Bxf5
7. Qxa1
8. e6 {I thought this was the best option in many variations. Black's pieces are just sad.JK. Exclam (!) is from me.} 
8. g6 {8...fxe69.Bg6+Kd810.Nf3Qxa210...Nd711.O-O∞11.Ne5⇆8...Nf69.exf7+JK. Mistake! note that here too, in the analysis, White is taking on f7 with the intuition that we are weakening Black's king. But the key point is that with our pawn on e6, Black will never be able to develop their kingside.9.Nf3+-JK.9...Kxf710.Nf3⩲8...Qxa29.exf7+Kxf710.Nf3Nf611.Ne5++-} 
9. exf7+ {Mistake! This helps Black unravel.9.Bd3+-JK. Black will never develop their pieces.} 
9. Kxf7 {After my next move, I wanted to bang my head against the table. Playing online sometimes feels different, and after calculating some variations, I played the second move in a variation.JK. White is doing great of course, and the takeaway here is that you need to be ready to have a deep think early in the game.} 
10. Nf3 {Terrible blunder in a brainfart moment that will never happen OTB.10.Bh3Nf610...Bg711.Nf311.Nf3In this position, I think that Black is barely hanging on. I don't know what the engine says, but g6, e6, and e5 are all weak, and the queen could go to d3 or e2 pretty soon. Black has a hard time coordinating, the extra material doesn't matter so much at this point.JK. I sense that after Nf3 or Ne2, intending Nf4, Black has no chance.10.Bc8I didn't go for this, but I'm not sure if that was the right decision (anyways, I didn't play what I wanted to play, which was Bh3 or this).10...Na6!Opening up the b-file will give Black too much counterplay.11.Bxb7Rb812.Qf3+-+10.c3gxf511.Qb3maybe this was better than Bh3, again going to trap the black queen and using the fact that the white queen is more active than the two rooks and that Black has poor king safety.} 
10. gxf5 {I wanted to resign at this point, but I thought it was too disrespectful for a Dojo classical tournament, and I will play it out and try to cause problems. Black still has king safety and development issues} 
11. Ne5+
11. Ke8
12. O-O
12. Nd7 {After analyzing, I think this was a critical mistake that made the game a lot more double-edged than it needed to be.} 
13. Nxd7
13. Kxd7
14. Qd3 {The threat of taking on f5 and getting in.JK. One reason I included this game is what Yossef says at the top: that even after we've really blown it, the position is so tactical that we still have great practical chances. This is true across the repertoire.} 
14. e6 {14...Qxa215.Qxf5+e616.Qf7+Ne7∓this is scary as hell, but maybe Black is a bit more coordinated here. He is still a rook up.} 
15. Nc3
15. Qxf1+ {After this move I was optimistic. My opponent was lower rated than me, and I thought it would be hard for him to convert with two rooks and a pawn against a queen. Also, in hindsight, it is really tricky to coordinate and start using the rooks and the extra pawn.I didn't consider White to be a bit better because of the material, but it is actually the time aspect and activity that is more relevant than two pawns in this position.JK. Great analysis, we see this dynamic in several variations of our repertoire: even if Black gets a big handful of pieces for the queen, the question is whether or not we have the initiative. And we have that here.15...Qb216.Rb1Qa317.Rxb7+Kc8-+I think Black is almost winning here, but it is tricky to stabilize.18.Rf718.Rb3∞18...Ne719.Qe3Kd719...Qd620.Qe520.Nxd5Qxe321.Nf6+Kd822.fxe3-+20.Rf6∞and e6 is falling.20...Qxc320...Rh621.Bxh6Bxh622.Rf6Bg723.Qxe6+Kc724.Rf720...Rg821.Qxh8+-} 
16. Kxf1
16. Bg7
17. a4 {Trying to create weaknesses for my queen to get into.JK. Too slow, we HAVE to get our c3-knight involved.17.Na4could be a better option just trying to jump to c5.17...b617...Bf818.Nc5+Bxc519.dxc5Ne720.Qd4here the queen gets in too, and the pawn on d6 could prove to be useful. Black has to tread lightly. JK. Great variation, I don't see how Black prevents our initiative on the dark squares.20...Rag821.Qe5Rh721...Rxg5sacrificing the exchange to avoid mating ideas on e7.22.Qd6+Ke823.hxg5±the queen is too active.22.Qd6+Ke823.Qxe6⩲White has at least equalized here, since he can just use his active queen to go after pawns. JK. I sense that White is clearly winning because Black can't coordinate their pieces.18.Qa6+-here the queen got in.} 
17. Nf6
18. f3
18. Rae8
19. a5
19. Kc8
20. Na4
20. Rhf8
21. Nc5 {21.a6b622.Qa3apparently, Black has too many weaknesses here, and the queen will get in.22...Rf723.Qd6Rc724.Bf4Ree725.Nxb6+axb626.a7+-} 
21. b6 {21...Nd7∞keeps the game going.21...Ne4∞for the psychological edge.} 
22. Qa6+
22. Kd8
23. axb6
23. axb6
24. Qxb6+
24. Ke7 {Cute mate. The bishop on g5 was useful at the end.} 
25. Qc7
